<a name="A First Slide">

<H1>A First Slide
</H1>


<P>
Open a new text document. Let's communicate the office way of drinking coffee. The first draft may look like this:
</P>


<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=80%><TR><TD bgcolor="#e5e5e5"><PRE>
<FONT COLOR="#000000">
  * Come when you are thirsty.

  * Make new coffee if the ... is empty.

  * Fill your cup (regardless of size).

  * Insert 0,50 into the box.
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TABLE>


<P>
This looks perfect - four points to state out. Start a point by a <CODE>*</CODE> character at the left margin, and complete it by an empty line. If it contains a lot of text, simply continue on the next line at any position like in
</P>


<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=80%><TR><TD bgcolor="#e5e5e5"><PRE>
<FONT COLOR="#000000">
  * Fill your cup
    (regardless of size).
</FONT></PRE></TD></TR></TABLE>


<P>
The lines will be automatically combined correctly until the documents end or an empty line follows. The whole thing is called a &quot;paragraph&quot;. Paragraphs are a base principle of PerlPoint.
</P>
